INSERT INTO `extra` (`term_id`, `type`, `id`, `value`) VALUES
('040D6A1B412A4cc6921882357A58F747', 'example', 1, 'A person, object, event, idea, process, etc.'),
('8E6626F259FF4ef1A8E4195531916E8F', 'example', 1, 'Idea, process, organization, etc.'),
('C941C5B14FFB4aecAA18427AF3D1435A', 'note', 1, 'All material entities have certain characteristics that can be described and therefore this concept is important for ontology purposes.'),
('95C4A86465B74046823106670EF95C77', 'note', 1, 'There is not complete agreement on the precise limits of ITS. Currently, the term is almost exclusively applied to ground-based travel of goods and people over significant distances. The term is viewed as including ferry systems, which often form an integral part of a local surface transport system; it is less clear if it includes long-distance sea-fairing ships. ITS is also generally applied to transport systems that cover a considerable distance (e.g., control systems for factory conveyance technologies are not often referred to as "ITS"). Some have suggested that air travel, which is arguably a transport system designed to move physical entities between points on the surface of the earth, should be included in the scope of the term, but this perspective is not universally accepted. It is expected that the exact limits of the term will be further refined as the technology matures.'),
('95C4A86465B74046823106670EF95C77', 'note', 2, '"Intelligent transportation system" is the American English equivalent.'),
('95C4A86465B74046823106670EF95C77', 'note', 3, 'Benefits potentially include, but are not limited to, increased safety, sustainability, efficiency, and comfort. '),
('95C4A86465B74046823106670EF95C77', 'note', 4, 'The long form (i.e., "intelligent transport system") is often used when the noun is used as a subject, whereas the abbreviation (i.e., "ITS") is often used to modify another noun (e.g., "Intelligent transport systems provide ITS services.").'),
('261629D58D7B439b8DAE5905D2EEF4D5', 'note', 1, 'A surface transport system might include tunnels, bridges, and similar elements.'),
('8648D088383A40a19D19B3E02A7060DF', 'note', 1, 'Transport systems can also include any supporting system, such as information and control systems.'),
('B2051EC4DBC44bffB1210761FC375378', 'example', 1, 'Generalised Enterprise Reference Architecture and Methodologies (GERAM) [ISO 15704] is an architecture framework.'),
('B2051EC4DBC44bffB1210761FC375378', 'example', 2, 'Reference Model of Open Distributed Processing (RM-ODP) [ISO/IEC 10746] is an architecture framework. '),
('FA25496536F542ee8EEECAE2225A828E', 'note', 1, 'A concern pertains to any influence on a system in its environment, including developmental, technological, business, operational, organizational, political, economic, legal, regulatory, ecological and social influences. '),
('BCD10BE481B544698858512B057E1D40', 'note', 1, 'The environment of a system includes developmental, technological, business, operational, organizational, political, economic, legal, regulatory, ecological and social influences.'),
('539D69676C04491081CB654FB9B87320', 'note', 1, 'Examples of model kinds include data flow diagrams, class diagrams, Petri nets, balance sheets, organization charts and state transition models.'),
('A55DFAE6A3594f3f9DCE94FACB4B44AC', 'note', 1, 'Within ITS, the preferred model for describing the communications view is based on the ITS-S reference architecture.'),
('B34FD020963F4c85BD2610D158A905D2', 'note', 1, 'The term "deployment view" is sometimes used within the broader ICT community, but the term "physical view" is preferred to prevent confusion between the physical view of a reference architecture and any part of a deployment architecture. '),
('B67D64896F6943cc98608CF4BB934A7D', 'note', 1, 'Within the US, the NTCIP standards identify an "information layer" on top of the traditional OSI stack; however, the purpose of this layer includes both information configuration and functionality. The ITS-S reference architecture separates these two roles between the management entity and the application entity.'),
('D2CFC0A0A5ED4c9cA02DABE3A56DF207', 'note', 1, 'Within the US, the NTCIP standards call the facilities layer the "application layer"; however, as this term is easily confused with both the OSI application layer and the application entity, the term should be avoided and qualified when used (e.g., OSI application layer).'),
('C55A586CEBC740c9A1E6B60B56701B60', 'note', 1, 'Within the IETF, the term "link layer" is used to describe the same functionality as the ITS-S access layer.'),
('C55A586CEBC740c9A1E6B60B56701B60', 'note', 2, 'Within the US, the NTCIP standards use the term "subnet layer" to describe the same functionality as the ITS-S access layer.'),
('4054E22B679E4ba691B836B9353A2A7E', 'note', 1, 'The full name of this layer is the networking and transport layer, but the term transnet layer provides a more concise name.'),
('4D42D0BA04584798BEB7CFD665901F33', 'note', 1, 'A document can be a single information item, or part of a larger information item.'),
('4D42D0BA04584798BEB7CFD665901F33', 'example', 1, 'A report, specification, manual, or book, in printed or electronic form.'),
('9D3AD00160DB4805AAAFAD93BD7CDF54', 'example', 1, 'A module might extend the functionality of another module.'),
('A7DCA2591555475e8CD8BF283937D2A4', 'example', 1, 'A road operator might enter into formal agreement(s) with the owner of a road and the owner(s) of the associated roadside equipment.'),
('8007F31A4CE246c6A005311E064AC4B1', 'example', 1, 'Every ITS component includes one or more modules.'),
('5F9BFC5DEFF748df88B4D6F471C1D8CD', 'note', 1, 'A function transforms inputs into outputs that may include the creation, modification, monitoring, or destruction of elements.'),
('EC65B14A2BF845deBCC48632F635C9FF', 'note', 1, 'The term "module" is used by the European FRAME architecture while the Architecture Reference for Cooperative and Intelligent Transportation (ARC-IT) uses the term "functional object".'),
('EC65B14A2BF845deBCC48632F635C9FF', 'example', 1, 'A vehicle OBE might include a "vehicle basic safety" functional object.'),
('9680D3EDB96947e2975441B520E3CFE4', 'note', 1, 'The term "information flow triple" is used extensively in the Architecture Reference for Cooperative and Intelligent Transportation (ARC-IT, http://arc-it.net).'),
('3783095C41E041c8B0CC1813CBCAEE44', 'note', 1, 'Physical objects are ITS components if they are an integral part of the system; otherwise they are terminators.'),
('8EA65F2D6F6347bf8FF4C5CD35C61C68', 'note', 1, 'Physical objects are represented as elements within the physical view and perform a role. Physical objects can be implemented as cloud-based systems.'),
('8EA65F2D6F6347bf8FF4C5CD35C61C68', 'note', 2, 'Within many ITS reference architectures, physical objects are placed into one of five categories: centre, support, field, vehicle, or traveller.'),
('98ACC203E1E34474AF1A04245619E6BF', 'note', 1, 'A terminator can exist within functional and physical views.'),
('AEDCDFD1175A4735AF8F91068BE5703F', 'note', 1, 'An ITS architecture might be a reference, planning, or deployment architecture. '),
('AEDCDFD1175A4735AF8F91068BE5703F', 'note', 2, 'The Harmonised Architecture Reference for Technical Standards (HARTS; http://htg7.org) is an example of an ITS reference architecture.'),
('CAC31494A311430cBB567F2A82C166EC', 'note', 1, 'The ITS-S reference architecture provides a model for describing communication.'),
('0875724C4E4C4527A11C1B5977FA6250', 'note', 1, 'Some countries use the term "regional architecture", but in international standards, the term "regional" is avoided due to its multiple meanings.\r\n '),
('7823F79833D54238B649F8A4D20F13C5', 'note', 1, 'Interface standards are based on a reference architecture, which should be explicitly described.'),
('5C989C1352B14d07BB1E631FC7D46F8F', 'note', 1, 'In order to exchange a value corresponding to a data concept, more information than an identifier and a definition might be needed. For a property, a data type is needed. Depending on the kind of property, other data elements such as unit of measure, and language, might be needed as well. The additional information can be given in the data dictionary, in a data specification that references the data concept or associated with the data themselves.'),
('8ED0B56A7A7C46369CAC281E4716F553', 'note', 1, 'The data concept registry contains meta-attributes about data concepts in terms of their names and representational forms as well as the semantics associated with the data concepts. A data concept registry may contain metadata that assists information interchange and re-use, both from the perspective of human users and for machine-interpretation of data concepts.\r\n '),
('8ED0B56A7A7C46369CAC281E4716F553', 'note', 2, 'A data registry typically includes advanced features for adding, retrieving, and working with its contents.'),
('DF674EF5FB8049aaBE03DC6E5FF03853', 'note', 1, 'Some TC 204 standards use the term "object class" for consistency with ISO 11179-1, but within ITS, the term "class" is more generally understood.'),
('DF674EF5FB8049aaBE03DC6E5FF03853', 'note', 2, 'This is semantically equivalent to a "class" as used within UML(ISO19505-2:2012).'),
('6ADFFDA7618A4047AE100991CBCE83C7', 'note', 1, 'A data element considered indivisible in one context (e.g., location) may be divisible in another context (e.g., latitude, longitude, and elevation).'),
('D0B512E1030A4b998CB13473D336CBFC', 'note', 1, 'A data frame can contain other data frames.'),
('D0B512E1030A4b998CB13473D336CBFC', 'note', 2, 'The grouping can be a set, sequence, or a choice.'),
('A5ED9D410EE248389659C4C127C6159A', 'note', 1, 'The term "dialog" represents the American English spelling.'),
('A5ED9D410EE248389659C4C127C6159A', 'note', 2, 'The term "dialogue" can be used when the interface context is known.'),
('C7D0D59CB4CF482c92AAA0D821A13A05', 'note', 1, 'Field systems can be permanently installed or transportable.'),
('C7D0D59CB4CF482c92AAA0D821A13A05', 'note', 2, 'The term "roadside system" is typically used to describe field systems along a roadside but can also be used to refer to kiosks and any other systems.'),
('C7D0D59CB4CF482c92AAA0D821A13A05', 'note', 3, 'Typically, field systems are located along the roadside.'),
('C7D0D59CB4CF482c92AAA0D821A13A05', 'note', 4, 'Typically, the operation of a field system is governed by management functions running in a centre system. '),
('C7D0D59CB4CF482c92AAA0D821A13A05', 'example', 1, 'traffic detector, camera, signal controller, message sign, tolling station'),
('23E6CD14703145869348FF4FB599A887', 'example', 1, 'Data distribution system, network time source, cooperative ITS credentials management system'),
('49FF108A0CA140d49A439CF9BBABA1BB', 'note', 1, 'The term "connected" does not imply support for any specific communications interface or ITS-S application process.'),
('5DAF919582BA4ebcA9458826C7601B83', 'note', 1, 'Connected roadside equipment typically provides ITS-related functionality but the term includes roadside equipment that only provide the ITS service of routing for short-range ireless technologies.'),
('5DAF919582BA4ebcA9458826C7601B83', 'note', 2, 'The term "connected vehicle roadside equipment" is used within the current version of the Architecture Reference for Cooperative and Intelligent Transportation (ARC-IT, http://arc-it.net).'),
('B6702EA11A52412eA44F00E7A7D44F40', 'note', 1, ''),
('B6702EA11A52412eA44F00E7A7D44F40', 'note', 2, 'ITS services that can be performed by ITS roadside equipment include surveillance, traffic control, information provision, payment transaction services, and/or enforcement'),
('B6702EA11A52412eA44F00E7A7D44F40', 'example', 1, 'traffic signal controller, variable message sign, vehicle detection'),
('3E33A4D7FC4341d981D249AC28E47690', 'example', 1, 'personal computer'),
('09AD781A2EFB4956A6DDEDD0F99E8870', 'example', 1, 'kiosk'),
('B2AFCEA42AC34410BBD8D0FDE1EB8B5C', 'note', 1, 'The exact term for this concept might change in the next version of this document.'),
('19370BF79EB84485AEAD2DDF5F784F2F', 'note', 1, 'ITS on-board equipment relates to any functionality. When there is a need to distinguish between core functionality and that by a special vehicle, the term can be further refined by indicating the type of vehicle to which the on-board equipment relates. For example, emergency vehicle on-board equipment can provide specialized functionality.'),
('19370BF79EB84485AEAD2DDF5F784F2F', 'note', 2, 'The on-board equipment may also perform other functions.'),
('E1D193F17654409cA350D9BECAAB4943', 'note', 1, 'An OBU implementation can also include ITS functionality.'),
('F1E402D380EE478c957A2FF53D9EA0C5', 'note', 1, 'The ITS station reference architecture is defined in ISO 21217.'),
('20C54C577219497797058A8BA5FD0D89', 'note', 1, 'ITS-S border router and ITS-S mobile router are ITS-S routers with added functionality, which is why they are separately excluded from the above definition.'),
